logo concept bao research group stanford university home people current alumni new member research research topics archived news wikilab lab members only publications press contact us visitors the bao molecule designed by benjamin tee the logo is fondly called the bao molecule lived and breathed by everyone as part of our research experience in the bao research group the design concept of the logo came about from the constant benzene and thiophene rings drawn all over the lab from whiteboards to fumehood covers to bench tops using simple hexagon and pentagon the shapes were connected such that the letters b a and o can be formed from the geometry of the final structure the vertical hexagons resembles an infinity sign representing the infinite possibilities available to a chemist or engineer that work with the materials synthesized by the group's excellent team of synthetic chemists the green open structure at the top left of the vertical infinity sign represents the budding leaves of a plant deriving it's nutrients from the bao molecule this was added to signify our group's efforts in photovoltaic cells in a green effort to synthesize organic materials that can potentially be used in large area photovoltaics copyright 2009 2011 all rights reserved credits bao group benjamin tee soumen barmen logo by benjamin tee
